title: 67's win fifth straight
text:
Ottawa 67s 
The kid got it done for the Ottawa 67's on Thursday. 
Austen Keating, Ottawa's first-round pick in 2015, extended the 67's winning streak to five games with a breakaway goal in overtime against the Windsor Spitifires. 
Keating also opened the scoring for the 67's in the 4-3 victory, tying the game in the second period before the teams traded goals a couple more times to force the extra session. 
It looked like Sam Studnicka's team-leading sixth of the year in the third would hold up as the winner, but Daniel Beaudoin tied things at three when he scored with four minutes to play in the third. 
Playing their first of three road games in four days, the 67's found themselves in an early hole after Cristiano DiGiacinto scored five minutes into the game to give the Spitfires the early lead. After Keating tied the game, Hayden McCool would restore Windsor's lead just over a minute later. 
Dante Salituro scored his fifth of the year on the power play to send the teams into the third tied. 
Leo Lazarev made 27 saves for the win, while Windsor's Michael Giugovaz turned aside 23 shots. 
Ottawa hasn't lost since opening the season with three-straight defeats. The 67's weekend road trip continues Friday when the visit the Flint Firebirds.
